{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain works where language itself—speaking, naming, or the right/wrong use of words—is made the explicit object of philosophical reflection (e.g., discussions of the origin or nature of names, signification, semiotics, or the philosophy of language akin to Cratylus or similar traditions).**\n\nWhile \"speech\" (often poetic eloquence or divine gift), \"words,\" or \"tongue\" appear frequently—especially in Old English Christian poetry (e.g., Andreas, Elene), Urdu ghazals (Iqbal, Ghalib, Zauq), and Dharmaśāstra texts (Smṛtis like Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Aṅgirasa Smṛti)—these are typically narrative, metaphorical, miraculous, or regulatory uses rather than meta-linguistic analysis. For instance:\n\n- Poetry contemplates the *power*, *beauty*, or *limitations* of speech as a human/divine faculty.[^1][^2]\n- Smṛtis prescribe *legal/ethical rules* for speech (e.g., avoiding harshness, defining conciliation).[^3][^4]\n\nNo representative passages can be pulled, as no work treats language as the central or reflective subject. The 37 works focus on theology, ethics, property, economics, devotion, and law, not linguistics.",
